Interview Definition

Insertion anomaly occurs when new information cannot be inserted because another unrelated piece of information is required.

3. Deletion Anomaly
Definition

Deletion anomaly occurs when deleting one record unintentionally deletes important information.

Example

Table

Student	Course	Teacher
Rahul	DBMS	Sharma
Amit	Java	Gupta

Suppose Rahul leaves college.

Delete Rahul.

Table becomes

Student	Course	Teacher
Amit	Java	Gupta

Now

Who teaches DBMS?

No record.

Teacher Sharma information has disappeared.

Although teacher still works in college.

Deleting student deleted teacher information.

This is

Deletion Anomaly
Real Life Example

Hospital

Patient	Doctor
Rahul	Dr. Sharma

Rahul gets discharged.

Delete record.

Now

Doctor Sharma disappears from database.

Doctor still exists.

But information is lost.

Deletion anomaly.

Another Example

Company

Employee	Department
Rahul	Cyber Security

Rahul resigns.

Delete row.

Now

Cyber Security department disappears.

Wrong.

Department still exists.

Interview Definition

Deletion anomaly occurs when deleting one record unintentionally removes other valuable information.

Why Do These Problems Occur?

Because multiple entities are stored in one table.

Example

Student

Teacher

Course

All are mixed.

This causes

Redundancy

↓

Repeated Data

↓

Anomalies
How Normalization Solves This?

Instead of one big table

We create multiple tables.

Student Table
StudentID	Student Name
101	Rahul
102	Amit
103	Priya
Teacher Table
TeacherID	Teacher Name	Phone
T1	Sharma	9999
T2	Gupta	8888
Course Table
CourseID	Course	TeacherID
C1	DBMS	T1
C2	Java	T2
Enrollment Table
StudentID	CourseID
101	C1
102	C1
103	C2

Now

Teacher phone changes?

Update only

Teacher Table

once.

No repetition.

New teacher joins?

Insert into Teacher table.

No students needed.

Student leaves?

Delete only Enrollment.

Teacher remains safe.

Real-Life Analogy

Imagine a school office.

Before Normalization

Every student form contains:

Principal Name
Principal Phone
School Address
Teacher Name
Teacher Phone

If the principal changes phone number,

You must update every student's form.

Thousands of updates!

After Normalization

Keep separate records:

Student Register
Teacher Register
Principal Register

If the principal changes phone number,

Update one record only.

That's the idea behind normalization.

Quick Comparison
Anomaly	What Happens?	Example
Update Anomaly	Same data must be updated in many places	Teacher phone changes; update every row
Insertion Anomaly	Cannot insert data without unrelated data	Cannot add a teacher until a student exists
Deletion Anomaly	Deleting one row removes other useful data	Deleting the last student also deletes teacher information
Memory Trick (Interview)

Remember the acronym UID:

U = Update Anomaly → Updating one fact requires changing it in many rows.
I = Insertion Anomaly → Inserting new information is impossible without unrelated data.
D = Deletion Anomaly → Deleting one record accidentally deletes important information.
